# Change Safety and Regression Rules

Use these rules for all feature work, refactors, and bug fixes.

## 1) Minimal Safe Diff

- one change should have one clear purpose
- do not mix unrelated cleanup into functional work
- do not mass-rename, move files, or reorder code without need
- prefer the narrowest change that solves the problem safely
- preserve stable interfaces where possible

## 2) Mandatory Impact Analysis

Before implementation, identify:
- touched modules
- dependent flows
- persistence impact
- cache/query invalidation impact
- domain invariant risk
- user-visible behavior risk

## 3) High-Risk Areas in Rememo

Any change touching these areas is medium-to-high risk by default:
- learning session creation or hydration
- review eligibility and timezone logic
- scoring or next-date scheduling calculations
- note tree movement, restore, or hard delete
- trash cleanup behavior
- study question generation or display in learning flows
- import/export transformations
- auth-gated bootstrapping and route loading

## 4) Regression Checklist

Check relevant items explicitly:
- existing pages still render
- note creation/editing still works
- tree operations still preserve parent/child structure
- trash, restore, and hard delete behavior still works
- due pages still appear correctly
- learning session still opens and progresses
- manual review still respects one-review-per-day rule
- scoped learning still works independently of global learning
- invalidated queries refresh the right surfaces
- loading/error/empty states remain coherent

## 5) Definition of Done

A task is not done until all relevant items are addressed:
- architecture rules respected
- requested behavior implemented
- no unrelated behavior changed
- type errors resolved
- tests added or updated where required
- manual verification completed for affected flows
- known risks documented

## 6) Manual QA Guidance

For affected flows, check:
- happy path
- repeated action
- refresh after action
- navigation away and back
- loading state
- empty state
- failure state
- edit then cancel
- delete then restore where relevant
- narrow viewport if UI structure changed

## 7) Stop Conditions

Stop and explain before continuing if:
- the requested change would break an invariant
- the safest solution requires expanding scope materially
- persistence shape or contract change becomes necessary
- a bug cannot be reproduced or the root cause is uncertain
